Date: Sun, 29 Oct 2000 16:24:41 -0800
From: Dr. Richard H. Evans <snaver@home.com>

West Nile Virus Transmission: Fecal Excretion
---------------------------------------------
In reference to the recent press release by Dr. McClean concerning
experimental West Nile virus in crows, it should be noted that West Nile
virus fecal excretion has been documented in waterfowl (Komar at CDC, I
believe) and chickens (DA Senne, et. al., Avian Diseases 44: 642-649, 2000).
Further, Steele, et. al. (KE Steele, et. al, Veterinary Pathology
37:208-244, 2000) noted extensive West Nile virus immunohistochemical
staining of intestinal sections in their study of the pathology of West Nile
virus from the Bronx Zoo in New York (they have a excellent photomicrograph
of such staining in a fish crow on page 221 of their paper).
Taken together with the crow study there appears to be little doubt that
West Nile virus infected birds excrete virus in their feces. Whereas, the
chicken study failed to demonstrate contagion or even seroconversion in
uninfected intimate contact controls, this still does not rule out the
possibility that in other species of birds fecal viral shedding may be of
sufficient duration and titer to infect birds in close contact or by
preening. On the other side of the coin, I am unfortunately (or fortunately,
depending on ones perspective) reminded daily that experimental findings
frequently do not manifest themselves in "the real world". Thus, while the
results of this study are very interesting indeed, they may not be directly
applicable to the "wild" situation.
--
Richard H. Evans, DVM, MS
Research Associate, Vector Borne Diseases
Orange County Vector Control
13001 Garden Grove Blvd.
Garden Grove, CA
<OCVCD@aol.com>
