From: Dr. Richard H. Evans <snaver@home.com>

West Nile virus transmission: Exclusion of Ectoparasites
--------------------------------------------------------
In regards the questions about the presence of ectoparasites on the crows in
the experimental study by Bob McClean, et. al., I had a telephone discussion
with Dr. McClean on Friday (27 Oct 2000) about the study and he informed me
that the birds were examined for ectoparasites and treated with Ivermectin
prior to the study which took place in a BSL-3 facility.
--
Richard H. Evans, DVM, MS
Research Associate
Orange County Vector Control
13001 Garden Grove Blvd.
Garden Grove, CA
<OCVCD@aol.com>
[Some questions are answered, and new ones posed. Transmission by
ectoparasites was excluded in the design of the bird-to-bird transmission
study. It has also been established that West Nile virus is excreted in the
feces of infected birds. What remains indeterminate, among other factors,
are the oral infectious dose and the infectivity of excreted feces. - Mod.CP
